{"title_page": "Rodrigo Cota de Maguaque", "text_new": "'''Rodrigo Cota de Maguaque''' (died c. 1498), [[Spain|Spanish]] [[poet]], who flourished towards the end of the 15th century, was born at [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]].\n\n==Life==\nLittle is known of him save that he was of [[Jewish]] origin. The ''Coplas de Migo<!-- or \"Mingo\" --> Revulgo'', the ''Coplas del Provincial'', and the first act of ''La Celestina'' have been ascribed to him on insufficient grounds.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nHe is undoubtedly the author of the ''Di\u00e1logo entre el amor y un viejo'', a striking dramatic poem first printed in the ''Cancionero general'' of 1511, and of a burlesque [[epithalamium]] written in 1472 or later. He abjured [[Judaism]] about the year 1497, and is believed to have died shortly afterwards.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n== See ==\n* ''\u00c9pithalame burlesque'', edited by [[Raymond Foulch\u00e9-Delbosc]], in the ''Revue hispanique'' (Paris, 1894), i. 69-72\n* [[Adolfo Bonilla y San Mart\u00edn]], ''Anales de la literatura espa\u00f1ola'' (Madrid, 1904), pp.&nbsp;164\u2013167.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{EB1911|wstitle=Cota de Maguaque, Rodrigo|volume=7}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cota, Rodigo, De Maguaque}}\n[[Category:1498 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish poets]]\n[[Category:Spanish Jews]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Spanish male poets]]\n\n\n{{spain-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Rodrigo Cota de Maguaque''' (died c. 1498), [[Spain|Spanish]] [[poet]], who flourished towards the end of the 15th century, was born at [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]].\n==Life==\nLittle is known of him save that he was of [[Jewish]] origin. The ''Coplas de Migo<!-- or \"Mingo\" --> Revulgo'', the ''Coplas del Provincial'', and the first act of ''La Celestina'' have been ascribed to him on insufficient grounds.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\nHe is undoubtedly the author of the ''Di\u00e1logo entre el amor y un viejo'', a striking dramatic poem first printed in the ''Cancionero general'' of 1511, and of a burlesque [[epithalamium]] written in 1472 or later. He abjured [[Judaism]] about the year 1497, and is believed to have died shortly afterwards.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}\n\n== See ==\n* ''\u00c9pithalame burlesque'', edited by [[Raymond Foulch\u00e9-Delbosc]], in the ''Revue hispanique'' (Paris, 1894), i. 69-72\n* [[Adolfo Bonilla y San Mart\u00edn]], ''Anales de la literatura espa\u00f1ola'' (Madrid, 1904), pp.&nbsp;164\u2013167.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{EB1911|wstitle=Cota de Maguaque, Rodrigo|volume=7}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cota, Rodigo, De Maguaque}}\n[[Category:1498 deaths]]\n[[Category:Spanish poets]]\n[[Category:Spanish Jews]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n[[Category:Spanish male poets]]\n\n\n{{spain-poet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodrigo_Cota_de_Maguaque"}
{"title_page": "Mandarin paradox", "text_new": "{{Short description|Ethical parable by Chateaubriand}}\nThe ''' Mandarin paradox''' is an [[ethics|ethical]] [[parable]] used to illustrate the difficulty of fulfilling [[Deontological ethics|moral obligation]]s when [[Punishment#In philosophy|moral punishment]] is unlikely or impossible, leading to [[moral disengagement]].<ref name=\"HZ19\">{{cite journal |last=Hanotte-Zawi\u015blak |first=Anna |title=Le retour du \u00abparadoxe du mandarin\u00bb dans la construction de l\u2019arriviste litt\u00e9raire au XIXe si\u00e8cle |publisher=Uniwersytet Gda\u0144ski |journal=Cahiers ERTA |date=2019-06-28 |issue=18 |pages=9-23 |url=http://cejsh.icm.edu.pl/cejsh/element/bwmeta1.element.ojs-issn-2353-8953-year-2019-issue-18-article-3313 |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> It has been used to underscore the fragility of ethical standards when [[moral agent]]s are separated by physical, cultural, or other distance, especially as facilitated by [[globalization]].<ref name=\"Delon13\">{{cite journal |last=Delon |first=Michel |title=De Diderot \u00e0 Balzac, le paradoxe du mandarin |journal=Italian Review of French Studies |volume=3 |doi=10.4000/rief.248 |url=https://journals.openedition.org/rief/248 |date=2013-12-15 |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> It was first posed by French writer [[Chateaubriand]] in ''\"[[The Genius of Christianity]]\"'' (1802):<ref name=\"CG94\">{{cite journal |last=Ginzburg |first=Carlo |title=Killing a Chinese Mandarin: The Moral Implications of Distance |journal=Critical Inquiry |volume=21 |issue=1 |date= Autumn 1994 |pages=46-60 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/1343886 |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nI ask  my own heart, I put to myself this question: \"If thou couldst by a mere wish kill a fellow-creature in China, and inherit his  fortune in Europe, with the supernatural conviction that the fact  would never be known, wouldst thou consent to form such a  wish?\" </blockquote>\n\nThe paradox is famously used to foreshadow the character development of the ''[[arriviste]]'' [[Eug\u00e8ne de Rastignac]] in [[Balzac]]'s novel ''[[P\u00e8re Goriot]]''.<ref name=\"HZ19\"/> Rastignac asks Bianchon if he recalls the paradox, to which Bianchon first replies that he is \"at [his] thirty-third mandarin,\" but then states that he would refuse to take an unknown man's life regardless of circumstance.<ref name=\"CG94\"/> Rastignac wrongly attributes the quote to [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]], which propagated to later writings.<ref name=\"Delon13\"/><ref name=\"Rousseau-authorship\">{{cite book |last=Falaky |first=Fay\u00e7al |chapter=Reverse Revolution: The Paradox of Rousseau's Authorship |title=Rousseau and Revolution |editor1-last=Lauritsen |editor1-first=Holger Ross |editor2-last=Thorup |editor2-first=Mikkel |series=Continuum Studies in Political Philosophy |publisher=Continuum |date=2011-09-15 |isbn=978-1441128973 |pages=83-97 |url=https://www.academia.edu/1957297/Reverse_Revolution_The_Paradox_of_Rousseaus_Authorship |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> \n\n==In fiction==\n* [[The Mandarin (novel)]] by Jos\u00e9 Maria de E\u00e7a de Queir\u00f3s\n* [[Button, Button (The Twilight Zone)|Button, Button]] by [[Richard Matheson]] (plus movie [[The Box (2009 film)]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography==\n* ''Champsaur F.,'' Le Mandarin, Paris, P. Ollendorff, 1895\u20101896 (r\u00e9imprim\u00e9 sous le nom ''L\u2019Arriviste'', Paris, Albin Michel, 1902)\n* ''Schneider L.'' Tuer le Mandarin // ''Le Gaulois'', 18 juillet 1926, no 17818\n* ''Paul Ronal.'' Tuer le mandarin // Revue de littirature comparee 10, no. 3 (1930): 520\u201323.\n* ''E. Latham'' // Une cita\udbc0\udc52on de Rousseau // Mercure de France, 1er juin 1947, no 1006, p. 393.\n* Barbey B. \u00abTuer le Mandarin\u00bb // ''Mercure de France'', 1er septembre 1947, no 1009\n* ''Laurence W. Keates''. Mysterious Miraculous Mandarin: Origins, Literary Paternity, Implications in Ethics // Revue de littirature comparee 40, no. 4 (1966): 497\u2013525,\n* ''Antonio Coimbra Martins.'' O mandarim assassinado // Ensaios Queirosianos: \u00ab0 mandarim assassinado\u00bb. \"0 incesto d\"os maias,' imitagdo capital\". (Lisbon, 1967), pp. 27\u201328.\n* ''Eric Hayot.'' The Hypothetical Mandarin: Sympathy, Modernity, and Chinese Pain. Oxford, New York: Oxford University Press, 2009\n\n[[Category:Thought experiments in ethics]]\n[[Category:Decision-making paradoxes]]\n{{Ethics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Ethical parable by Chateaubriand}}\nThe ''' Mandarin paradox''' is an [[ethics|ethical]] [[parable]] used to illustrate the difficulty of fulfilling [[Deontological ethics|moral obligation]]s when [[Punishment#In philosophy|moral punishment]] is unlikely or impossible, leading to [[moral disengagement]].<ref name=\"HZ19\">{{cite journal |last=Hanotte-Zawi\u015blak |first=Anna |title=Le retour du \u00abparadoxe du mandarin\u00bb dans la construction de l\u2019arriviste litt\u00e9raire au XIXe si\u00e8cle |publisher=Uniwersytet Gda\u0144ski |journal=Cahiers ERTA |date=2019-06-28 |issue=18 |pages=9-23 |url=http://cejsh.icm.edu.pl/cejsh/element/bwmeta1.element.ojs-issn-2353-8953-year-2019-issue-18-article-3313 |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> It has been used to underscore the fragility of ethical standards when [[moral agent]]s are separated by physical, cultural, or other distance, especially as facilitated by [[globalization]].<ref name=\"Delon13\">{{cite journal |last=Delon |first=Michel |title=De Diderot \u00e0 Balzac, le paradoxe du mandarin |journal=Italian Review of French Studies |volume=3 |doi=10.4000/rief.248 |url=https://journals.openedition.org/rief/248 |date=2013-12-15 |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> It was first posed by French writer [[Chateaubriand]] in ''\"[[The Genius of Christianity]]\"'' (1802):<ref name=\"CG94\">{{cite journal |last=Ginzburg |first=Carlo |title=Killing a Chinese Mandarin: The Moral Implications of Distance |journal=Critical Inquiry |volume=21 |issue=1 |date= Autumn 1994 |pages=46-60 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/1343886 |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref>\n<blockquote>\nI ask  my own heart, I put to myself this question: \"If thou couldst by a mere wish kill a fellow-creature in China, and inherit his  fortune in Europe, with the supernatural conviction that the fact  would never be known, wouldst thou consent to form such a  wish?\" </blockquote>\n\nThe paradox is famously used to foreshadow the character development of the ''[[arriviste]]'' [[Eug\u00e8ne de Rastignac]] in [[Balzac]]'s novel ''[[P\u00e8re Goriot]]''.<ref name=\"HZ19\"/> Rastignac asks Bianchon if he recalls the paradox, to which Bianchon first replies that he is \"at [his] thirty-third mandarin,\" but then states that he would refuse to take an unknown man's life regardless of circumstance.<ref name=\"CG94\"/> Rastignac wrongly attributes the quote to [[Jean-Jacques Rousseau]], which propagated to later writings.<ref name=\"Delon13\"/><ref name=\"Rousseau-authorship\">{{cite book |last=Falaky |first=Fay\u00e7al |chapter=Reverse Revolution: The Paradox of Rousseau's Authorship |title=Rousseau and Revolution |editor1-last=Lauritsen |editor1-first=Holger Ross |editor2-last=Thorup |editor2-first=Mikkel |series=Continuum Studies in Political Philosophy |publisher=Continuum |date=2011-09-15 |isbn=978-1441128973 |pages=83-97 |url=https://www.academia.edu/1957297/Reverse_Revolution_The_Paradox_of_Rousseaus_Authorship |access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> \n\n==In fiction==\n* [[The Mandarin (novel)]] by Jos\u00e9 Maria de E\u00e7a de Queir\u00f3s\n* [[Button, Button (The Twilight Zone)|Button, Button]] by [[Richard Matheson]] (plus movie [[The Box (2009 film)]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography==\n* ''Champsaur F.,'' Le Mandarin, Paris, P. Ollendorff, 1895\u20101896 (r\u00e9imprim\u00e9 sous le nom ''L\u2019Arriviste'', Paris, Albin Michel, 1902)\n* ''Schneider L.'' Tuer le Mandarin // ''Le Gaulois'', 18 juillet 1926, no 17818\n* ''Paul Ronal.'' Tuer le mandarin // Revue de littirature comparee 10, no. 3 (1930): 520-23.\n* ''E. Latham'' // Une cita\udbc0\udc52on de Rousseau // Mercure de France, 1er juin 1947, no 1006, p. 393.\n* Barbey B. \u00abTuer le Mandarin\u00bb // ''Mercure de France'', 1er septembre 1947, no 1009\n* ''Laurence W. Keates''. Mysterious Miraculous Mandarin: Origins, Literary Paternity, Implications in Ethics // Revue de littirature comparee 40, no. 4 (1966): 497\u2014525,\n* ''Antonio Coimbra Martins.'' O mandarim assassinado // Ensaios Queirosianos: \u00ab0 mandarim assassinado\u00bb. \"0 incesto d\"os maias,' imitagdo capital\". (Lisbon, 1967), pp. 27-28.\n* ''Eric Hayot.'' The Hypothetical Mandarin: Sympathy, Modernity, and Chinese Pain. Oxford, New York: Oxford University Press, 2009\n\n[[Category:Thought experiments in ethics]]\n[[Category:Decision-making paradoxes]]\n{{Ethics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 520-23 \u2192 520\u201323 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandarin_paradox"}
{"title_page": "Rodney Koeneke", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Rodney Koeneke\n| birth_date = September 12, 1968  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n| nationality       =                   American\n| alma_mater        =                 [[University of California, Berkeley]]<br>[[Stanford University]]\n| genre = poetry\n}}\n\n'''Rodney Koeneke''' (born September 12, 1968) is an American poet.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/rodney-koeneke|title=Rodney Koeneke|work=The Poetry Foundation|date=2014| location=USA}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Omaha, Nebraska]], Koeneke was raised in [[Tucson, Arizona]] and [[Hacienda Heights, California]]. He graduated with a BA in [http://history.berkeley.edu/ History] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1990, where he lived in [[Barrington Hall (Berkeley, California)|Barrington Hall]], and from [[Stanford University]] with a PhD in [http://humsci.stanford.edu/ History and Humanities] in 1997.\n \nKoeneke is the author of several books and chapbooks of poetry, including ''Body & Glass'' (2018),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wavepoetry.com/products/body-glass|title=Body & Glass|author=Rodney Koeneke|publisher=Wave Books|year=2018}}</ref> ''Etruria'' (2014),<ref>\n{{cite web|url= http://publishersweekly.com/978-1-933517-82-7|title=Etruria|author=Rodney Koeneke|publisher=Wave Books|year=2014}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite journal|url=http://reviews.libraryjournal.com/2014/04/books/nonfic/arts-humanities/thirty-amazing-poetry-titles-for-spring-2014/|work=LibraryJournal.com|title=Thirty Amazing Poetry Titles for Spring 2014|author=Barbara Hoffert, Annalisa Pesek|year=2014}}</ref>\n''Musee Mechanique'' (2006),<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.blazevox.org/Rodney-march06.pdf|title=Musee Mechanique|publisher=BlazeVOX|year=2006|author=Rodney Koenke}}</ref>\nand ''Rouge State'' (2003).<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.bookslut.com/features/2006_04_008430.php|title=JUDGING A BOOK BY ITS COVER: PAVEMENT SAW PRESS|author=Melissa Fisher|work=bookslut.com|year=2006}}</ref>\nHis work has appeared in\n''[[The Brooklyn Rail]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.brooklynrail.org/2013/11/poetry/11-poems-koeneke|work=The Brooklyn Rail|author=Rodney Koeneke|title=eleven|year=2013}}</ref>\n''Fence'', \n''[[Granta]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.granta.com/New-Writing/Pyjamas|work=Granta|title=Pyjamas|author=Rodney Koeneke|year=2014}}</ref> ''[[Gulf Coast (magazine)|Gulf Coast]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://gulfcoastmag.org/journal/26.2/after-lunch,-some-poems/|author=Rodney Koeneke|year=2014|title=26.2|work=Gulf Coast Magazine}}</ref>\n''[[Harper's Magazine|Harper's]]'', ''Harriet'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/harriet/author/rodney-koeneke/|author=Rodney Koenke|work=Harriet the Blog|publisher=The Poetry Foundation|year=2014|title=Author Archive}}</ref>\n''[[The Nation]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.thenation.com/authors/rodney-koeneke|author=Rodney Koeneke|work=The Nation|title=slow poem}}</ref>\n''[[New American Writing]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.newamericanwriting.com/25/koeneke.htm|work=New American Writing|author=Rodney Koenke|title=Humanism is Cheese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828164721/http://newamericanwriting.com/25/koeneke.htm|archivedate=2008-08-28|df=}}</ref>\n''[[Poetry (magazine)|Poetry]]'', \nand ''[[Zyzzyva (magazine)|Zyzzyva]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.zyzzyva.org/index-of-published-works/|work=zyzzyva|title=Index of Published Works}}</ref>\n \nHe lives in [[Portland, Oregon]].\n\n==Works==\n\n===Full Length Poetry===\n*''Body & Glass'' (Wave Books, 2018) {{ISBN|9781940696683}}\n*''Etruria'' (Wave Books, 2014) {{ISBN|978-1-933517-81-0}}\n*''Musee Mechanique'' (BlazeVOX, 2006) {{ISBN|978-1934289006}}\n*''Rouge State'' (Pavement Saw, 2003) {{ISBN|978-1886350632}}\n\n===Chapbooks===\n*''Seven for Boetticher & Other Poems'' (Hooke Press, 2015)\n*''Names of the Hits (of Diane Warren)'' (OMG!, 2010)\n*''Rules for Drinking Forties'' (Cy Press, 2009)\n*''On the Clamways'' (Sea Lamb, 2004)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''Empires of the Mind: I.A. Richards and Basic English in China, 1929-1979'' (Stanford University Press, 2004) {{ISBN|978-0804748223}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.modampo.blogspot.com/|title=Author's Website}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.wavepoetry.com/products/rodney-koeneke/|title=Rodney Koeneke\u2019s author page at Wave Books}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/rodney-koeneke/|title=Rodney Koeneke : The Poetry Foundation}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.poetrysociety.org/psa/poetry/crossroads/own_words/Rodney_Koeneke/|title=Rodney Koeneke on \u2013 Poetry Society of America}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://bookhaven.stanford.edu/tag/rodney-koeneke/|title=Rodney Koeneke - The Book Haven}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://latenightlibrary.org/poetrys-special-way-of-folding-a-conversation-with-rodney-koeneke/|title=A Conversation with Rodney Koeneke \u2013 Late Night Library}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://studioonereadingseries.blogspot.com/2014/11/a-conversation-rodney-koeneke-sheila.html|title=Studio One Reading Series: A Conversation: Rodney Koeneke}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://poetasradio.blogspot.com/2013/06/june-2-2013-rodney-koeneke.html|title=Poet as Radio: June 2, 2013 Rodney Koeneke}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koeneke, Rodney}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Writers from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = Rodney Koeneke\n| birth_date = September 12, 1968  <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place = [[Omaha, Nebraska]]\n| nationality       =                   American\n| alma_mater        =                 [[University of California, Berkeley]]<br>[[Stanford University]]\n| genre = poetry\n}}\n\n'''Rodney Koeneke''' (born September 12, 1968) is an American poet.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/rodney-koeneke|title=Rodney Koeneke|work=The Poetry Foundation|date=2014| location=USA}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Omaha, Nebraska]], Koeneke was raised in [[Tucson, Arizona]] and [[Hacienda Heights, California]]. He graduated with a BA in [http://history.berkeley.edu/ History] from the [[University of California, Berkeley]] in 1990, where he lived in [[Barrington Hall (Berkeley, California)|Barrington Hall]], and from [[Stanford University]] with a PhD in [http://humsci.stanford.edu/ History and Humanities] in 1997.\n \nKoeneke is the author of several books and chapbooks of poetry, including ''Body & Glass'' (2018),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wavepoetry.com/products/body-glass|title=Body & Glass|author=Rodney Koeneke|publisher=Wave Books|year=2018}}</ref> ''Etruria'' (2014),<ref>\n{{cite web|url= http://publishersweekly.com/978-1-933517-82-7|title=Etruria|author=Rodney Koeneke|publisher=Wave Books|year=2014}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite journal|url=http://reviews.libraryjournal.com/2014/04/books/nonfic/arts-humanities/thirty-amazing-poetry-titles-for-spring-2014/|work=LibraryJournal.com|title=Thirty Amazing Poetry Titles for Spring 2014|author=Barbara Hoffert, Annalisa Pesek|year=2014}}</ref>\n''Musee Mechanique'' (2006),<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.blazevox.org/Rodney-march06.pdf|title=Musee Mechanique|publisher=BlazeVOX|year=2006|author=Rodney Koenke}}</ref>\nand ''Rouge State'' (2003).<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.bookslut.com/features/2006_04_008430.php|title=JUDGING A BOOK BY ITS COVER: PAVEMENT SAW PRESS|author=Melissa Fisher|work=bookslut.com|year=2006}}</ref>\nHis work has appeared in\n''[[The Brooklyn Rail]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.brooklynrail.org/2013/11/poetry/11-poems-koeneke|work=The Brooklyn Rail|author=Rodney Koeneke|title=eleven|year=2013}}</ref>\n''Fence'', \n''[[Granta]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.granta.com/New-Writing/Pyjamas|work=Granta|title=Pyjamas|author=Rodney Koeneke|year=2014}}</ref> ''[[Gulf Coast (magazine)|Gulf Coast]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://gulfcoastmag.org/journal/26.2/after-lunch,-some-poems/|author=Rodney Koeneke|year=2014|title=26.2|work=Gulf Coast Magazine}}</ref>\n''[[Harper's Magazine|Harper's]]'', ''Harriet'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/harriet/author/rodney-koeneke/|author=Rodney Koenke|work=Harriet the Blog|publisher=The Poetry Foundation|year=2014|title=Author Archive}}</ref>\n''[[The Nation]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.thenation.com/authors/rodney-koeneke|author=Rodney Koeneke|work=The Nation|title=slow poem}}</ref>\n''[[New American Writing]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.newamericanwriting.com/25/koeneke.htm|work=New American Writing|author=Rodney Koenke|title=Humanism is Cheese|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080828164721/http://newamericanwriting.com/25/koeneke.htm|archivedate=2008-08-28|df=}}</ref>\n''[[Poetry (magazine)|Poetry]]'', \nand ''[[Zyzzyva (magazine)|Zyzzyva]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.zyzzyva.org/index-of-published-works/|work=zyzzyva|title=Index of Published Works}}</ref>\n \nHe lives in [[Portland, Oregon]].\n\n==Works==\n\n===Full Length Poetry===\n*''Body & Glass'' (Wave Books, 2018) {{ISBN|9781940696683}}\n*''Etruria'' (Wave Books, 2014) {{ISBN|978-1-933517-81-0}}\n*''Musee Mechanique'' (BlazeVOX, 2006) {{ISBN|978-1934289006}}\n*''Rouge State'' (Pavement Saw, 2003) {{ISBN|978-1886350632}}\n\n===Chapbooks===\n*''Seven for Boetticher & Other Poems'' (Hooke Press, 2015)\n*''Names of the Hits (of Diane Warren)'' (OMG!, 2010)\n*''Rules for Drinking Forties'' (Cy Press, 2009)\n*''On the Clamways'' (Sea Lamb, 2004)\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''Empires of the Mind: I.A. Richards and Basic English in China, 1929-1979'' (Stanford University Press, 2004) {{ISBN|978-0804748223}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.modampo.blogspot.com/|title=Author's Website}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.wavepoetry.com/products/rodney-koeneke/|title=Rodney Koeneke\u2019s author page at Wave Books}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.poetryfoundation.org/bio/rodney-koeneke/|title=Rodney Koeneke : The Poetry Foundation}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.poetrysociety.org/psa/poetry/crossroads/own_words/Rodney_Koeneke/|title=Rodney Koeneke on \u2013 Poetry Society of America}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://bookhaven.stanford.edu/tag/rodney-koeneke/|title=Rodney Koeneke - The Book Haven}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://latenightlibrary.org/poetrys-special-way-of-folding-a-conversation-with-rodney-koeneke/|title=A Conversation with Rodney Koeneke \u2013 Late Night Library}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://studioonereadingseries.blogspot.com/2014/11/a-conversation-rodney-koeneke-sheila.html|title=Studio One Reading Series: A Conversation: Rodney Koeneke}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://poetasradio.blogspot.com/2013/06/june-2-2013-rodney-koeneke.html|title=Poet as Radio: June 2, 2013 Rodney Koeneke}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koeneke, Rodney}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century American poets]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Writers from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodney_Koeneke"}
{"title_page": "Lifeboat ethics", "text_new": "[[Image:Titanic lifeboat.jpg|right|thumb|Hardin uses the metaphor of a lifeboat to make his argument]]\n'''Lifeboat ethics''' is a metaphor for resource distribution proposed by the [[ecology|ecologist]] [[Garrett Hardin]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite magazine\n|url=http://www.garretthardinsociety.org/articles/art_lifeboat_ethics_case_against_helping_poor.html\n|title=Lifeboat Ethics: the Case Against Helping the Poor\n|accessdate=July 29, 2006\n|last=Hardin|first=Garrett\n|date=September 1974|magazine=[[Psychology Today]]\n}}</ref>\n\nHardin's [[metaphor]] describes a [[Lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboat]] bearing 50 people, with room for ten more. The lifeboat is in an ocean surrounded by a hundred swimmers.  The \"[[ethics]]\" of the situation stem from the [[dilemma]] of whether (and under what circumstances) swimmers should be taken aboard the lifeboat.\n\nHardin compared the lifeboat metaphor to the [[Spaceship Earth]] model of resource distribution, which he criticizes by asserting that a spaceship would be directed by a single leader{{snd}}a captain{{snd}}which the Earth lacks. Hardin asserts that the spaceship model leads to the [[tragedy of the commons|''tragedy of the commons'']].  In contrast, the lifeboat metaphor presents individual lifeboats as [[wealth|rich]] nations and the swimmers as poor nations.\n\nOther issues which can be raised include:\n* Is it acceptable to deny an obviously dying passenger food and water to save it for others with a better chance to make it?\n* Is it acceptable to ''jettison'' the dying passenger (knowing they will die within minutes) to make room for someone else?\n* If food is low:\n** is cannibalism of corpses acceptable after they die? \n** is it acceptable, if it is certain they are going to die in a day or two, to murder them to preserve resources or to let someone on the boat?\n** is it acceptable, if it is certain they are going to die in a day or two, to murder them in order to commit cannibalism of their corpse where this will allow the survivors to survive for several additional weeks?\n\nThe third point regarding low supply of food had happened in reality before. A British court, in the ruling of ''[[R v Dudley and Stephens]]'' ruled that necessity is not a defense of murder.\n\nLifeboat ethics is closely related to [[environmental ethics]], [[utilitarianism]], and issues of [[resource depletion]].  Hardin uses lifeboat ethics to question [[policies]] such as [[foreign aid]], [[immigration]], and [[food bank]]s.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Balloon debate]]\n* [[Carrying capacity]]\n* [[Food for Peace]]\n* [[Intergenerational ethics]]\n* [[Population control]]\n* [[Ratchet effect]]\n* [[Repugnant conclusion]]\n* [[Triage]]\n* [[Trolley problem]]\n* [[Women and children first]]\n* [[Zero population growth]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.garretthardinsociety.org/articles/art_lifeboat_ethics_case_against_helping_poor.html Lifeboat ethics - a case against helping the poor (Garrett Hardin Society)]\n*Hardin, G. 1974. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11661143 \"Living on a lifeboat\"] ''Bioscience'' 24 (10), 561\u2013568.\n\n[[Category:Thought experiments in ethics]]\n[[Category:Environmentalism]]\n\n{{environment-stub}}\n{{ethics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[Image:Titanic lifeboat.jpg|right|thumb|Hardin uses the metaphor of a lifeboat to make his argument]]\n'''Lifeboat ethics''' is a metaphor for resource distribution proposed by the [[ecology|ecologist]] [[Garrett Hardin]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite magazine\n|url=http://www.garretthardinsociety.org/articles/art_lifeboat_ethics_case_against_helping_poor.html\n|title=Lifeboat Ethics: the Case Against Helping the Poor\n|accessdate=July 29, 2006\n|last=Hardin|first=Garrett\n|date=September 1974|magazine=[[Psychology Today]]\n}}</ref>\n\nHardin's [[metaphor]] describes a [[Lifeboat (shipboard)|lifeboat]] bearing 50 people, with room for ten more. The lifeboat is in an ocean surrounded by a hundred swimmers.  The \"[[ethics]]\" of the situation stem from the [[dilemma]] of whether (and under what circumstances) swimmers should be taken aboard the lifeboat.\n\nHardin compared the lifeboat metaphor to the [[Spaceship Earth]] model of resource distribution, which he criticizes by asserting that a spaceship would be directed by a single leader{{snd}}a captain{{snd}}which the Earth lacks. Hardin asserts that the spaceship model leads to the [[tragedy of the commons|''tragedy of the commons'']].  In contrast, the lifeboat metaphor presents individual lifeboats as [[wealth|rich]] nations and the swimmers as poor nations.\n\nOther issues which can be raised include:\n* Is it acceptable to deny an obviously dying passenger food and water to save it for others with a better chance to make it?\n* Is it acceptable to ''jettison'' the dying passenger (knowing they will die within minutes) to make room for someone else?\n* If food is low:\n** is cannibalism of corpses acceptable after they die? \n** is it acceptable, if it is certain they are going to die in a day or two, to murder them to preserve resources or to let someone on the boat?\n** is it acceptable, if it is certain they are going to die in a day or two, to murder them in order to commit cannibalism of their corpse where this will allow the survivors to survive for several additional weeks?\n\nThe third point regarding low supply of food had happened in reality before. A British court, in the ruling of ''[[R v Dudley and Stephens]]'' ruled that necessity is not a defense of murder.\n\nLifeboat ethics is closely related to [[environmental ethics]], [[utilitarianism]], and issues of [[resource depletion]].  Hardin uses lifeboat ethics to question [[policies]] such as [[foreign aid]], [[immigration]], and [[food bank]]s.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Balloon debate]]\n* [[Carrying capacity]]\n* [[Food for Peace]]\n* [[Intergenerational ethics]]\n* [[Population control]]\n* [[Ratchet effect]]\n* [[Repugnant conclusion]]\n* [[Triage]]\n* [[Trolley problem]]\n* [[Women and children first]]\n* [[Zero population growth]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.garretthardinsociety.org/articles/art_lifeboat_ethics_case_against_helping_poor.html Lifeboat ethics - a case against helping the poor (Garrett Hardin Society)]\n*Hardin, G. 1974. [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/11661143 \"Living on a lifeboat\"] ''Bioscience'' 24 (10), 561-568.\n\n[[Category:Thought experiments in ethics]]\n[[Category:Environmentalism]]\n\n{{environment-stub}}\n{{ethics-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 561-568 \u2192 561\u2013568", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lifeboat_ethics"}
{"title_page": "Rodger Kamenetz", "text_new": "<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:RKportrait.jpg|thumb|Rodger Kamenetz, 2006{{Pufc|1=RKportrait.jpg|date=10 March 2013}}]] -->\n[[File:Dalai Lama Zalmancolor300dpi.jpg|thumb|The XIV Dalai Lama and Rabbi Zalman Schachter-Shalomi during the historic Jewish-Buddhist dialogue in Dharamsala, India, October 25, 1990]]\n\n'''Rodger Kamenetz''' (born 1950) is an American poet and author.\nHe is best known as the author of ''[[The Jew in the Lotus]]'' (1994), an account of the historic dialogue between [[rabbi]]s and the XIV [[Dalai Lama]].\n\n==Life and career==\nKamenetz was born in [[Baltimore]] and educated at [[Yale]], [[Stanford]] and [[Johns Hopkins University]]. He currently lives in [[New Orleans]] and is Professor Emeritus, retiring with a dual appointment as Professor of English and Professor of Religious Studies at [[Louisiana State University|LSU]] where he was also an LSU Distinguished Professor and  Erich and Lea Sternberg Honors Professor. He currently works privately with clients, using dreams in a process of spiritual direction. Kamenetz is married to [[Moira Crone]], a novelist and short story writer. He is the father of [[Anya Kamenetz]], also an author, and Kezia Kamenetz.\n\n===Poetry===\nAt the age of 16, Kamenetz entered [[Yale University]], where he gave readings and published with poets [[Alan Bernheimer]] and [[Kit Robinson]] (later associated with the [[Language poets]]), and studied with [[Ted Berrigan]]. His first book, ''The Missing Jew'' (Dryad, 1979, was influenced by the [[Objectivist poets]], especially [[Charles Reznikoff]], whom he met at Stanford in 1973. Both poets relied on plain diction and paid attention to American Jewish identity and culture. Another enduring influence was [[Robert Duncan (poet)]], whom Kamenetz also met at that time, and later interviewed extensively about Duncan's interest in the [[Zohar]] and Jewish mysticism.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kamenetz|first=Rodger|title=Realms of Being: An interview with Robert Duncan|journal=The Southern Review|year=1985|volume=21|issue=1|pages=5\u201325}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Wagstaff|first=Christopher|title=A Poet's Mind: Collected Interviews with Robert Duncan, 1960-1985|year=2012|publisher=North Atlantic Books|location=Berkeley, California|isbn=9781583944547|pages=387\u2013410}}</ref> \nKamenetz typed ''The Missing Jew'' on a single continuous scroll, and the poems developed as commentaries on previous poems, as in the Jewish literary tradition of [[midrash]]. Joel Lewis, writing in the '''Forward''', said, \"Mr. Kamenetz recovers Jewishness as a field for discourse, not sentimentalized imagery. In direct and imaginative address, he puts the question of Jewishness under discussion with large parts of honesty and humor.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Joel|title=A modern day Rashi|newspaper=The Forward|date=December 11, 1992}}</ref> \nKamenetz continued to add to the book, and a new edition, nearly double in size, appeared in 1991 as ''The Missing Jew: New and Selected Poems'' (Time Being, 1991). His poems were anthologized in ''Voices Within the Ark'' (Avon, 1979), ''Jewish American Poetry'' (Brandeis, 2000), ''Jewish in America'' (U. of Michigan Press), ''Bearing the Mystery'' (Eerdmans), ''Best Jewish Writing 2003'' (Jossey Bass), ''Blood to Remember: American Poets on the Holocaust'' (Time Being), ''Telling and Remembering: a Century of American Jewish Poetry'' (Beacon, 1997), and ''The Prairie Schooner Anthology of Contemporary Jewish American Writing'' (Nebraska, 1998). In ''The Lowercase Jew'' (Northwestern, 2003), Kamenetz adopted a form of verse essay to address issues of literary anti-Semitism. The title poem speaks to [[T.S. Eliot]]'s use of a lower case spelling of \"jew\" in his poetry; another retells an incident in which \"Allen Ginsberg Forgives Ezra Pound on Behalf of the Jews.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Kamenetz|first=Rodger|title=Allen Ginsberg Forgives Ezra Pound on Behalf of the Jews|url=http://blogs.forward.com/the-arty-semite/133838/allen-ginsberg-forgives-ezra-pound-on-behalf-of-th/|publisher=The Forward|accessdate=December 9, 2010}}</ref> Kamenetz's sixth  book of poetry, \"[https://www.amazon.com/Die-Next-You-Rodger-Kamenetz/dp/1926616502 To Die Next To You]\" (Six Gallery Press, 2013) derives primarily from his experience with dreamwork.<ref>{{cite web|last=Liebovitz|first=Liel|title=Rodger Kamenetz Will Explain Your Dreams|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/149978/rodger-kamenetz-will-explain-your-dreams|publisher=Tablet|accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref> His seventh book of poetry, \"[https://www.amazon.com/Yonder-Rodger-Kamenetz/dp/1944884580 Yonder]\" (Lavender Ink, 2019) \"brims with respect for the prose poetry genre, with homages to forebears from Baudelaire to Max Jacob, Russel Edson to Kafka.\"\n\n===Prose===\nAfter the death of his mother in 1980, Kamenetz turned from poetry to the autobiographical essay in ''Terra Infirma''  (University of Arkansas, 1985) and reprinted by Schocken Books in 1999.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bernstein|first=Richard|title=Terra Infirma:Penetrating the Mystery of a Mother's Silence|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/03/21/daily/032699terra-book-review.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 26, 1999}}</ref>  The book is structured as the interpretation of a single dream of his late mother, which Kamenetz modeled on [[Michel Butor]]'s ''Histoire extraordinaire: essai sur un r\u00eave de Baudelaire'' (1961). \nIn October 1990, Kamenetz was invited to observe an historic dialogue between rabbis and the [[XIV Dalai Lama]] in Dharamsala, India. The [[Dalai Lama]] had asked the Jewish delegates to share with him \"the secret of Jewish spiritual survival in exile.\"  His account of this exchange, [[The Jew in the Lotus]] (1994), was a popular success and became an international best-seller. Writing in the [[New York Times]], [[Verlyn Klinkenborg]] cited its broader relevance as a book \"about the survival of esoteric traditions in a world bent on destroying them.\" <ref>{{cite news|last=Klinkenborg|first=Verlyn|title=Going to See the Lama|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/24/books/going-to-see-the-lama.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 24, 1994}}</ref> The book was primarily potent in capturing an ongoing engagement in the US between Jews, often highly secularized, and Buddhist teachings. Kamenetz popularized the term [[Jewish Buddhist|JUBU]] or [[Jewish Buddhist]], interviewing poet [[Allen Ginsberg]], [[vipassana]] teacher [[Joseph Goldstein (writer)|Joseph Goldstein]], [[Ram Dass]] and other American Jews involved with bringing Eastern traditions to the West.  \nThe book also made prominent a Jewish mystical response to Eastern spirituality in the [[Jewish renewal]] movement, led by Rabbi [[Zalman Schachter-Shalomi]], and [[Jewish meditation]] as taught by Rabbi Jonathan Omer-Man. \n''The Jew in the Lotus'' inspired a PBS documentary of the same name produced and directed by Laurel Chiten, released theatrically in New York, Los Angeles and Boston, and subsequently on Independent Lens on   September 1, 1999.<ref>{{cite web|last=ITVS|title=The Jew in the Lotus|url=http://www.itvs.org/films/jew-in-the-lotus}}</ref> \nKamenetz followed ''The Jew in the Lotus'' with ''Stalking Elijah: Adventures with Today's Jewish Mystical Masters'' (Harper, 1997), which received the [[National Jewish Book Award]] for Jewish Thought in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/awards/national-jewish-book-awards/past-winners?category=30766|title=Past Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Jewish Book Council|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> Kamenetz interviews a number of Jewish leaders who attempt to blend together Jewish mysticism, feminism and innovations in prayer and meditation practice. Among them were Rabbis [[Zalman Schachter-Shalomi]], Jonathan Omer-Man, [[Arthur Green]] and [[Shefa Gold]]. The book ends with the account of a seder held in Dharamsala India, which included as guests the Tibetan teacher Geshe [[Sonam Rinchen (buddhist geshe)|Sonam Rinchen]]. During that same visit, Kamenetz met with the [[Dalai Lama]], which inspired him to work with the Interfaith Action Network of the International Campaign to free the young Panchen Lama [[Gedhun Choekyi Nyima]] from Chinese government detainment. The world's youngest prisoner of conscience, the Panchen Lama's eighth birthday fell during the first week of Passover. Struck by this coincidence, Kamenetz created a nationwide campaign of [[Passover Seder]]s for Tibet,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|title=Make Your Own Tradition: Redefining Seders for Today|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/10/nyregion/make-your-own-tradition-redefining-seders-for-today.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> uniting the Jewish memory of slavery and oppression in Egypt long ago with the lack of religious freedom in today's Tibet under Chinese rule. A special seder was held in Washington D.C. on April 24, 1997 and attended by the Dalai Lama, as well as by numerous U.S. dignitaries and celebrities, including Supreme Court Justice [[Stephen Breyer]] and [[Adam Yauch]] of the Beastie Boys.<ref>{{cite news|last=Niebuhr|first=Gustav|title=Adding a Contemporary Ring to an Ancient Story|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/26/us/adding-a-contemporary-ring-to-an-ancient-story.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 26, 1997}}</ref> The seder, as well as Kamenetz's visit with the Dalai Lama in 1997 was featured in the 1999 documentary, ''The Jew in the Lotus'' and is recounted in ''Stalking Elijah'' <ref>{{cite book|last=Kamenetz|first=Rodger|title=Stalking Elijah|year=1997|publisher=Harper San Francisco|isbn=0060642319|pages=[https://archive.org/details/stalkingelijahad00kame/page/327 327\u2013329]|url=https://archive.org/details/stalkingelijahad00kame/page/327}}</ref> \nIn fall 2007, Harper One published ''The History of Last Night's Dream'' which explores the spiritual possibilities of dreaming from Genesis to now. [[Oprah Winfrey]] interviewed the author about the book in a two-part XM radio broadcast in her ''Soul Series'' in August 2008. The material was subsequently webcast. [http://www.oprah.com/article/spirit/inspiration/pkgoprahssoulserieswebcast/20080825_oaf_oss_rkamenetz]\nSchocken/Nextbook Press published ''Burnt Books'' in October 2010. It is a dual biography of Rabbi [[Nachman of Bratslav]] and [[Franz Kafka]].\n\n== References==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''The Missing Jew''  (Dryad Press/Tropos Press, 1979) poetry.\n* ''Nympholepsy''  (Dryad Press, 1985) poetry.\n* ''Terra Infirma''  (U. of Arkansas Press, 1985) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1877770574 The Missing Jew: New and Selected Poems]'' (Time Being Books, 1991) poetry.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/The-Jew-Lotus-Rediscovery-Identity/dp/0061367397  The Jew in the Lotus]'' (Harper San Francisco, 1994) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/Stuck-Poems-Midlife-Rodger-Kamenetz/dp/1568090331  Stuck: Poems Midlife]''  (Time Being Books, 1997) poetry\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0060642327 Stalking Elijah]'' (Harper San Francisco, 1997) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/Terra-Infirma-Memoir-Mothers-Life/dp/0805211101  Terra Infirma: a memoir of my mother's life in mine]'' (Shocken, 1999) non-fiction, reprint.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0810151529 The Lowercase Jew]'' (Northwestern, 2003) poetry.\n* \"[https://www.amazon.com/The-Jew-Lotus-Rediscovery-Identity/dp/0061367397   The Jew in the Lotus (PLUS) With an afterword by the author.]\" (HarperOne, 2007) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0061237949 The History of Last Night's Dream]'' (HarperOne, 2007) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0805242570 Burnt Books: Rabbi Nachman of Bratslav and Franz Kafka]'' (Schocken/Nextbook, 2010) non-fiction.\n*\"[https://www.amazon.com/Die-Next-You-Rodger-Kamenetz/dp/1926616502 To Die Next To You]\" (Six Gallery Press, 2013) poetry\n*\"[https://www.lavenderink.org/site/shop/yonder/ Yonder]\" (Lavender Ink, 2019) poetry\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kamenetz.com Website]\n* [https://vimeo.com/ondemand/172444 The Jew in the Lotus movie]\n* [http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1673745,00.html Interview with TIME]\n* [http://www.nextbook.org/cultural/feature.html?id=746  NEXTBOOK Interview]\n* [https://vimeo.com/12803524 OPRAH WINFREY VIDEO INTERVIEW]\n*[http://imagejournal.org/page/artist-of-the-month/rodger-kamenetz  Image Journal Artist of the Month]\n*[http://nextbookpress.com/books/265/burnt-books Burnt Books Nextbook website]\n*[http://thenaturaldream.com/shift-network-interview-with-rodger-kamenetz/ Natural Dreamwork: Shift Network Interview]\n*[https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/the-reading-life-with-rodger-kamenetz/id508845918?i=1000427115460&mt=2 YONDER on WWNO]\n*[https://www.lavenderink.org/site/books/rodger-kamenetz/ Author page at Lavender Ink.]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kamenetz, Rodger}}\n[[Category:American religious writers]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish poets]]\n[[Category:Louisiana State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:RKportrait.jpg|thumb|Rodger Kamenetz, 2006{{Pufc|1=RKportrait.jpg|date=10 March 2013}}]] -->\n[[File:Dalai Lama Zalmancolor300dpi.jpg|thumb|The XIV Dalai Lama and Rabbi Zalman Schachter-Shalomi during the historic Jewish-Buddhist dialogue in Dharamsala, India, October 25, 1990]]\n\n'''Rodger Kamenetz''' (born 1950) is an American poet and author.\nHe is best known as the author of ''[[The Jew in the Lotus]]'' (1994), an account of the historic dialogue between [[rabbi]]s and the XIV [[Dalai Lama]].\n\n==Life and career==\nKamenetz was born in [[Baltimore]] and educated at [[Yale]], [[Stanford]] and [[Johns Hopkins University]]. He currently lives in [[New Orleans]] and is Professor Emeritus, retiring with a dual appointment as Professor of English and Professor of Religious Studies at [[Louisiana State University|LSU]] where he was also an LSU Distinguished Professor and  Erich and Lea Sternberg Honors Professor. He currently works privately with clients, using dreams in a process of spiritual direction. Kamenetz is married to [[Moira Crone]], a novelist and short story writer. He is the father of [[Anya Kamenetz]], also an author, and Kezia Kamenetz.\n\n===Poetry===\nAt the age of 16, Kamenetz entered [[Yale University]], where he gave readings and published with poets [[Alan Bernheimer]] and [[Kit Robinson]] (later associated with the [[Language poets]]), and studied with [[Ted Berrigan]]. His first book, ''The Missing Jew'' (Dryad, 1979, was influenced by the [[Objectivist poets]], especially [[Charles Reznikoff]], whom he met at Stanford in 1973. Both poets relied on plain diction and paid attention to American Jewish identity and culture. Another enduring influence was [[Robert Duncan (poet)]], whom Kamenetz also met at that time, and later interviewed extensively about Duncan's interest in the [[Zohar]] and Jewish mysticism.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kamenetz|first=Rodger|title=Realms of Being: An interview with Robert Duncan|journal=The Southern Review|year=1985|volume=21|issue=1|pages=5\u201325}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Wagstaff|first=Christopher|title=A Poet's Mind: Collected Interviews with Robert Duncan, 1960-1985|year=2012|publisher=North Atlantic Books|location=Berkeley, California|isbn=9781583944547|pages=387\u2013410}}</ref> \nKamenetz typed ''The Missing Jew'' on a single continuous scroll, and the poems developed as commentaries on previous poems, as in the Jewish literary tradition of [[midrash]]. Joel Lewis, writing in the '''Forward''', said, \"Mr. Kamenetz recovers Jewishness as a field for discourse, not sentimentalized imagery. In direct and imaginative address, he puts the question of Jewishness under discussion with large parts of honesty and humor.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Lewis|first=Joel|title=A modern day Rashi|newspaper=The Forward|date=December 11, 1992}}</ref> \nKamenetz continued to add to the book, and a new edition, nearly double in size, appeared in 1991 as ''The Missing Jew: New and Selected Poems'' (Time Being, 1991). His poems were anthologized in ''Voices Within the Ark'' (Avon, 1979), ''Jewish American Poetry'' (Brandeis, 2000), ''Jewish in America'' (U. of Michigan Press), ''Bearing the Mystery'' (Eerdmans), ''Best Jewish Writing 2003'' (Jossey Bass), ''Blood to Remember: American Poets on the Holocaust'' (Time Being), ''Telling and Remembering: a Century of American Jewish Poetry'' (Beacon, 1997), and ''The Prairie Schooner Anthology of Contemporary Jewish American Writing'' (Nebraska, 1998). In ''The Lowercase Jew'' (Northwestern, 2003), Kamenetz adopted a form of verse essay to address issues of literary anti-Semitism. The title poem speaks to [[T.S. Eliot]]'s use of a lower case spelling of \"jew\" in his poetry; another retells an incident in which \"Allen Ginsberg Forgives Ezra Pound on Behalf of the Jews.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Kamenetz|first=Rodger|title=Allen Ginsberg Forgives Ezra Pound on Behalf of the Jews|url=http://blogs.forward.com/the-arty-semite/133838/allen-ginsberg-forgives-ezra-pound-on-behalf-of-th/|publisher=The Forward|accessdate=December 9, 2010}}</ref> Kamenetz's sixth  book of poetry, \"[https://www.amazon.com/Die-Next-You-Rodger-Kamenetz/dp/1926616502 To Die Next To You]\" (Six Gallery Press, 2013) derives primarily from his experience with dreamwork<ref>{{cite web|last=Liebovitz|first=Liel|title=Rodger Kamenetz Will Explain Your Dreams|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/149978/rodger-kamenetz-will-explain-your-dreams|publisher=Tablet|accessdate=October 23, 2013}}</ref>. His seventh book of poetry, \"[https://www.amazon.com/Yonder-Rodger-Kamenetz/dp/1944884580 Yonder]\" (Lavender Ink, 2019) \"brims with respect for the prose poetry genre, with homages to forebears from Baudelaire to Max Jacob, Russel Edson to Kafka.\"\n\n===Prose===\nAfter the death of his mother in 1980, Kamenetz turned from poetry to the autobiographical essay in ''Terra Infirma''  (University of Arkansas, 1985) and reprinted by Schocken Books in 1999.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bernstein|first=Richard|title=Terra Infirma:Penetrating the Mystery of a Mother's Silence|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/03/21/daily/032699terra-book-review.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 26, 1999}}</ref>  The book is structured as the interpretation of a single dream of his late mother, which Kamenetz modeled on [[Michel Butor]]'s ''Histoire extraordinaire: essai sur un r\u00eave de Baudelaire'' (1961). \nIn October 1990, Kamenetz was invited to observe an historic dialogue between rabbis and the [[XIV Dalai Lama]] in Dharamsala, India. The [[Dalai Lama]] had asked the Jewish delegates to share with him \"the secret of Jewish spiritual survival in exile.\"  His account of this exchange, [[The Jew in the Lotus]] (1994), was a popular success and became an international best-seller. Writing in the [[New York Times]], [[Verlyn Klinkenborg]] cited its broader relevance as a book \"about the survival of esoteric traditions in a world bent on destroying them.\" <ref>{{cite news|last=Klinkenborg|first=Verlyn|title=Going to See the Lama|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/07/24/books/going-to-see-the-lama.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 24, 1994}}</ref> The book was primarily potent in capturing an ongoing engagement in the US between Jews, often highly secularized, and Buddhist teachings. Kamenetz popularized the term [[Jewish Buddhist|JUBU]] or [[Jewish Buddhist]], interviewing poet [[Allen Ginsberg]], [[vipassana]] teacher [[Joseph Goldstein (writer)|Joseph Goldstein]], [[Ram Dass]] and other American Jews involved with bringing Eastern traditions to the West.  \nThe book also made prominent a Jewish mystical response to Eastern spirituality in the [[Jewish renewal]] movement, led by Rabbi [[Zalman Schachter-Shalomi]], and [[Jewish meditation]] as taught by Rabbi Jonathan Omer-Man. \n''The Jew in the Lotus'' inspired a PBS documentary of the same name produced and directed by Laurel Chiten, released theatrically in New York, Los Angeles and Boston, and subsequently on Independent Lens on   September 1, 1999.<ref>{{cite web|last=ITVS|title=The Jew in the Lotus|url=http://www.itvs.org/films/jew-in-the-lotus}}</ref> \nKamenetz followed ''The Jew in the Lotus'' with ''Stalking Elijah: Adventures with Today's Jewish Mystical Masters'' (Harper, 1997), which received the [[National Jewish Book Award]] for Jewish Thought in 1997.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jewishbookcouncil.org/awards/national-jewish-book-awards/past-winners?category=30766|title=Past Winners|last=|first=|date=|website=Jewish Book Council|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-23}}</ref> Kamenetz interviews a number of Jewish leaders who attempt to blend together Jewish mysticism, feminism and innovations in prayer and meditation practice. Among them were Rabbis [[Zalman Schachter-Shalomi]], Jonathan Omer-Man, [[Arthur Green]] and [[Shefa Gold]]. The book ends with the account of a seder held in Dharamsala India, which included as guests the Tibetan teacher Geshe [[Sonam Rinchen (buddhist geshe)|Sonam Rinchen]]. During that same visit, Kamenetz met with the [[Dalai Lama]], which inspired him to work with the Interfaith Action Network of the International Campaign to free the young Panchen Lama [[Gedhun Choekyi Nyima]] from Chinese government detainment. The world's youngest prisoner of conscience, the Panchen Lama's eighth birthday fell during the first week of Passover. Struck by this coincidence, Kamenetz created a nationwide campaign of [[Passover Seder]]s for Tibet,<ref>{{cite news|last=Hoffman|first=Jan|title=Make Your Own Tradition: Redefining Seders for Today|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/10/nyregion/make-your-own-tradition-redefining-seders-for-today.html?pagewanted=all&src=pm|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> uniting the Jewish memory of slavery and oppression in Egypt long ago with the lack of religious freedom in today's Tibet under Chinese rule. A special seder was held in Washington D.C. on April 24, 1997 and attended by the Dalai Lama, as well as by numerous U.S. dignitaries and celebrities, including Supreme Court Justice [[Stephen Breyer]] and [[Adam Yauch]] of the Beastie Boys.<ref>{{cite news|last=Niebuhr|first=Gustav|title=Adding a Contemporary Ring to an Ancient Story|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/26/us/adding-a-contemporary-ring-to-an-ancient-story.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 26, 1997}}</ref> The seder, as well as Kamenetz's visit with the Dalai Lama in 1997 was featured in the 1999 documentary, ''The Jew in the Lotus'' and is recounted in ''Stalking Elijah'' <ref>{{cite book|last=Kamenetz|first=Rodger|title=Stalking Elijah|year=1997|publisher=Harper San Francisco|isbn=0060642319|pages=[https://archive.org/details/stalkingelijahad00kame/page/327 327\u2013329]|url=https://archive.org/details/stalkingelijahad00kame/page/327}}</ref> \nIn fall 2007, Harper One published ''The History of Last Night's Dream'' which explores the spiritual possibilities of dreaming from Genesis to now. [[Oprah Winfrey]] interviewed the author about the book in a two-part XM radio broadcast in her ''Soul Series'' in August 2008. The material was subsequently webcast. [http://www.oprah.com/article/spirit/inspiration/pkgoprahssoulserieswebcast/20080825_oaf_oss_rkamenetz]\nSchocken/Nextbook Press published ''Burnt Books'' in October 2010. It is a dual biography of Rabbi [[Nachman of Bratslav]] and [[Franz Kafka]].\n\n== References==\n<references/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''The Missing Jew''  (Dryad Press/Tropos Press, 1979) poetry.\n* ''Nympholepsy''  (Dryad Press, 1985) poetry.\n* ''Terra Infirma''  (U. of Arkansas Press, 1985) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/1877770574 The Missing Jew: New and Selected Poems]'' (Time Being Books, 1991) poetry.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/The-Jew-Lotus-Rediscovery-Identity/dp/0061367397  The Jew in the Lotus]'' (Harper San Francisco, 1994) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/Stuck-Poems-Midlife-Rodger-Kamenetz/dp/1568090331  Stuck: Poems Midlife]''  (Time Being Books, 1997) poetry\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0060642327 Stalking Elijah]'' (Harper San Francisco, 1997) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/Terra-Infirma-Memoir-Mothers-Life/dp/0805211101  Terra Infirma: a memoir of my mother's life in mine]'' (Shocken, 1999) non-fiction, reprint.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0810151529 The Lowercase Jew]'' (Northwestern, 2003) poetry.\n* \"[https://www.amazon.com/The-Jew-Lotus-Rediscovery-Identity/dp/0061367397   The Jew in the Lotus (PLUS) With an afterword by the author.]\" (HarperOne, 2007) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0061237949 The History of Last Night's Dream]'' (HarperOne, 2007) non-fiction.\n* ''[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0805242570 Burnt Books: Rabbi Nachman of Bratslav and Franz Kafka]'' (Schocken/Nextbook, 2010) non-fiction.\n*\"[https://www.amazon.com/Die-Next-You-Rodger-Kamenetz/dp/1926616502 To Die Next To You]\" (Six Gallery Press, 2013) poetry\n*\"[https://www.lavenderink.org/site/shop/yonder/ Yonder]\" (Lavender Ink, 2019) poetry\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kamenetz.com Website]\n* [https://vimeo.com/ondemand/172444 The Jew in the Lotus movie]\n* [http://www.time.com/time/arts/article/0,8599,1673745,00.html Interview with TIME]\n* [http://www.nextbook.org/cultural/feature.html?id=746  NEXTBOOK Interview]\n* [https://vimeo.com/12803524 OPRAH WINFREY VIDEO INTERVIEW]\n*[http://imagejournal.org/page/artist-of-the-month/rodger-kamenetz  Image Journal Artist of the Month]\n*[http://nextbookpress.com/books/265/burnt-books Burnt Books Nextbook website]\n*[http://thenaturaldream.com/shift-network-interview-with-rodger-kamenetz/ Natural Dreamwork: Shift Network Interview]\n*[https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/the-reading-life-with-rodger-kamenetz/id508845918?i=1000427115460&mt=2 YONDER on WWNO]\n*[https://www.lavenderink.org/site/books/rodger-kamenetz/ Author page at Lavender Ink.]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kamenetz, Rodger}}\n[[Category:American religious writers]]\n[[Category:American male poets]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish poets]]\n[[Category:Louisiana State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Johns Hopkins University alumni]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Baltimore]]\n[[Category:Writers from New Orleans]]\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodger_Kamenetz"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Singapore}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore\n<!--Difficult to update, so no longer appropriate\n| map2            = COVID-19 Cases in Singapore by Planning Areas.svg\n| legend2         = {{center|Map of planning areas with confirmed (red) coronavirus cases (as of 11 March)}}\n-->| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Singapore]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 23 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=23|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 460<ref name=\"worldometers\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |title=worldometers.info |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200129195657/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ |archive-date=29 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| deaths          = 6<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\">{{Cite web |url=https://coronaboard.com/ |title=COVID-19 Dashboard |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331135805/https://coronaboard.com/ |archive-date=31 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 1,910<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.coronatracker.com/country/sg |title=Corona Tracker Overview |access-date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325143811/https://www.coronatracker.com/country/sg/ |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| active          = \n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19}}\n| First Case detected: = \n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore''' is part of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first case of COVID-19 was confirmed on 23 January.<ref name=\"Abdullah 2020\" /> To combat COVID-19, a multi-ministerial committee was formed on 22 January with Minister for National Development [[Lawrence Wong]] and Minister for Health [[Gan Kim Yong]] as the co-chairs and [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] and [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] and Minister for Finance [[Heng Swee Keat]] as advisors.<ref name=\"ST22Jan\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/default-document-library/multi-ministry-taskforce-on-wuhan-coronavirus-and-tor---final.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321054236/https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/default-document-library/multi-ministry-taskforce-on-wuhan-coronavirus-and-tor---final.pdf |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 3 April, Singapore announced a stringent set of preventive measures which were collectively called a 'circuit breaker'. This will be applied from 7 April to 4 May 2020.\n[[Singapore]] contributed US$500,000 to support [[WHO]] efforts against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Singapore contributes US$500,000 to support WHO efforts against COVID-19 |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-contributes-s-500-000-to-support-who-covid-19-efforts-12568566 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNA |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325020159/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-contributes-s-500-000-to-support-who-covid-19-efforts-12568566 |archive-date=25 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Singapore medical cases chart}}\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe top plot shows the total number of cases as a function of time (by date) since 23 January 2020, the date of the first reported case in Singapore. The bottom plot shows the number of new cases as reported each day.\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|colors=orange, blue, red\n| legend=Legend\n| width = 900\n| height = 350\n| xAxisTitle = Date (day/month)\n| yAxisTitle = Total no. of cases (cumulative)\n| y1Title=Confirmed\n| y2Title=Recovered\n| y3Title=Deaths\n| xAxisAngle = -65\n| yGrid= |xGrid= \n| x =  23/1, 24/1, 25/1, 26/1, 27/1, 28/1, 29/1, 30/1, 31/1, 1/2, 2/2, 3/2, 4/2, 5/2, 6/2, 7/2, 8/2, 9/2, 10/2, 11/2, 12/2, 13/2, 14/2, 15/2, 16/2, 17/2, 18/2, 19/2, 20/2, 21/2, 22/2, 23/2, 24/2, 25/2, 26/2, 27/2, 28/2, 29/2, 1/3, 2/3, 3/3, 4/3, 5/3, 6/3, 7/3, 8/3, 9/3, 10/3, 11/3, 12/3, 13/3, 14/3, 15/3, 16/3, 17/3, 18/3, 19/3, 20/3, 21/3, 22/3, 23/3, 24/3, 25/3, 26/3, 27/3, 28/3, 29/3, 30/3, 31/3, 1/4, 2/4, 3/4, 4/4, 5/4, 6/4, 7/4, 8/4, 9/4\n| y1 = 1, 3, 3, 4, 5, 7, 10, 13, 16, 18, 18, 18, 24, 28, 30, 33, 40, 43, 45, 47, 50, 58, 67, 72, 75, 77, 81, 84, 85, 86, 89, 89, 90, 91, 93, 96, 98, 102, 106