ella McNamara\n|4 episodes\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[All My Children]]''\n|Judge Brauer\n|Soap Opera<br>Unknown episodes\n|-\n|1994-1998\n|''[[Law & Order]]''\n|Deirdre Powell\n|3 episodes\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Black and Blue]]''\n|Ann Benedetto\n|TV movie\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Witness Protection]]''\n|Cindy's mother\n|TV movie\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[The Jury (TV series)|The Jury]]''\n|Jackie Ochs\n|Episode: \"Too Jung to Die\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[The American Experience]]''\n|Family member\n|\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]''\n|Herself\n|Episode: Digital Nation\" \n|-\n|2011\n|''[[The Good Wife (TV series)|The Good Wife]]''\n|Loni Goslin\n|Episode: \"In Sickness\"\n|-\n|2000-2011\n|''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n|[[Judge Lena Petrovsky]]\n|43 episodes\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Homeland (TV series)|Homeland]]''\n|Grandma Lois\n|Episode: \"[[Tin Man Is Down]]\"\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1961\n|''Becket''\n|Gwendolyn\n|\n|-\n|1961\n|''[[A Far Country]]''\n|Replacement performer\n|\n|-\n|1964\n|''Fiddler on the Roof''\n|Tzeitel\n|\n|-\n|1970\n|''Company''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1971\n|''Follies''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1973\n|''[[A Little Night Music]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1976\n|''[[Pacific Overtures]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[On the Twentieth Century]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1979\n|''Evita''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1979\n|''Sweeney Todd''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[A Doll's Life]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Into The Woods]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|\"Absence\"\n|Helen Bastion\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{|  class=\"wikitable\"  width=\"100%\"\n|- \n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Film or series\n! Result\n|-\n|1988\n|[[Casting Society of America]] Artios Award\n|Best Casting for a Feature Film, Drama\n|''The Last Emperor''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|2009\n|[[Strasbourg International Film Festival]] Award\n|Best Actress\n|''Beautiful Hills of Brooklyn''\n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0581008|name=Joanna Merlin}}\n* {{IBDB name|52828}}\n* {{iobdb name|5394}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Merlin, Joanna}}\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:American stage actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Casting directors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n[[Category:Tisch School of the Arts faculty]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Joanna Merlin\n| birth_name    = Joann Ratner\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1931|7|15|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], U.S.\n| occupation    = Actress, teacher, author, casting director\n| years_active  = 1956&ndash;present\n| parents       = Harry Ratner <br /> Toni Merlin Ratner\n| children      = 2\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Martin Lubner|1950|1955|end=}} <br /> {{marriage|David Dretzin|1965}}\n}}\n\n'''Joanna Merlin''' (born July 15, 1931) is an American actress and casting director who has worked with [[Stephen Sondheim]] and starred in the original [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]''. She has written two acting guides<ref name=\"book\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/8236331-auditioning|title=Auditioning: An Actor Friendly Guide by Joanna Merlin|publisher=Good Reads|accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref><ref name=\"dvd\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7378689-master-classes-in-the-michael-chekhov-technique|title=Master Classes in the Michael Chekhov Tecnhique by Joanna Merlin|publisher=Good Reads|accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref> and is a faculty member of [[New York University]]'s graduate acting program.<ref name=\"nyu\">{{cite web|url=http://gradacting.tisch.nyu.edu/object/MerlinJ.html|title=Graduate Acting Faculty Directory|publisher=[[New York University]]|accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref> In recent years, she has become known for her recurring role on ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'' as Judge Lena Petrovsky.\n\n==Early life==\nJoann Ratner, who later took her mother's maiden name, was born in [[Chicago, Illinois]], to Toni Merlin and Harry Ratner, a [[Jewish]] grocer.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/74/Joanna-Merlin.html|title=Joanna Merlin Biography|publisher=Film Reference|accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref><ref>[http://memim.com/joanna-merlin.html \"Joanna Merlin\" Profile]. Memim.com.  Accessed October 2015.</ref> Her family also included her older sister Harriet Glickman (1926-2020) who had gained recognition when she helped persuade [[Charles Schulz]] to add a black character to his [[Peanuts]] strip.<ref>David E. Slotnik, \"Harriet Glickman, Who Pushed 'Peanuts' to Add a Black Character, Dies at 93,\" ''New York Times'', April 3, 2020, https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/03/arts/harriet-glickman-dead-peanuts.html.</ref>  Merlin first acted on stage at age 11, joining a community theatre production, ''Too Many Marys''.<ref name=\"interview\">{{cite web|url=http://www.backstage.com/bso/esearch/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=671005|title=Audition Advice From an Industry Vet: Joanna Merlin|first=Sherry|last=Eaker|date=2000-11-10|accessdate=2012-06-20|publisher=Back Stage}}</ref> Merlin graduated from [[UCLA]]<ref name=\"allmovie\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmovie.com/artist/joanna-merlin-p48569|title=Joanna Merlin - Movie and Film Biography|publisher=All Movie|first=Hal|last=Erickson|accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref> and later studied under [[Michael Chekhov]], learning his world-renowned acting technique. She has been described as the last student of Michael Chekhov who is still alive and teaching.<ref name=\"nyu\" />\n\n==Career==\nMerlin made her first screen appearance in [[Cecil B. DeMille]]'s film ''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]'' in 1956. Five years later, she made her Broadway debut in ''[[Becket]]''<ref name=\"bio\" /> before playing Tzeitel in [[Harold Prince]]'s production of ''Fiddler on the Roof''. She left the cast of ''Fiddler on the Roof'' before the end of its tour to take care of her two small children<ref name=\"interview\" /> but Harold Prince gave her the opportunity to become involved in casting with a more flexible schedule. ''[[Company (musical)|Company]]'' was the first musical for which Merlin served as the casting director. She was also in charge of casting for such plays as ''[[Follies]]'', ''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'' and ''[[Sweeney Todd: The Demon Barber of Fleet Street (musical)|Sweeney Todd]]''. \n\nIn 1986, she served as casting director for the [[John Carpenter]] film, ''[[Big Trouble in Little China]].''\n\nAfter making appearances in several feature films, including the movie ''[[Fame (1980 film)|Fame]]'', in which she played Miss Olivia Berg, a classical dance teacher; Merlin appeared in the [[NBC]] crime drama ''[[Law & Order]]'' in 1992 as a defense attorney.  Like many actors from that show, she went on to play other characters in the ''Law & Order'' franchise - another defense attorney in the original show and a more recurring role as Judge Lena Petrovsky, a judge who was very stern, by-the-book, and has scolded or sanctioned, at various times, ADAs [[Casey Novak]] ([[Diane Neal]]) and [[Alexandra Cabot]] ([[Stephanie March]]) and Detective (now Lieutenant) [[Olivia Benson]] ([[Mariska Hargitay]]), in its first spin-off ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''. In the latter role, she appeared in every season between the years 2000 and 2011.\n\nIn 2001, Joanna Merlin wrote ''Auditioning: An Actor-Friendly Guide''<ref name=\"book\" /> and in 2007, shared her knowledge of the theatre industry in the instructional video ''Master Classes in the Michael Chekhov Technique''.<ref name=\"dvd\" /> She teaches in New York University's graduate acting program at the [[Tisch School of the Arts]]<ref name=\"nyu\" /> and in 1999, founded the Michael Chekhov Association where she teaches acting workshops.<ref name=\"micha\">{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelchekhov.org/Merlin.htm|title=Joanna Merlin|publisher=The Michael Chekhov Association|accessdate=2012-06-20}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n|1956\n|''[[The Ten Commandments (1956 film)|The Ten Commandments]]''\n|Jethro's daughter\n|\n|-\n|1958\n|''Weddings and Babies''\n|Josie\n|\n|-\n|1975\n|''[[Hester Street (film)|Hester Street]]''\n|Jake's landlady\n|\n|-\n|1979\n|''[[All That Jazz (film)|All That Jazz]]''\n|Nurse Pierce\n|\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Fame (1980 film)|Fame]]''\n|Miss Berg\n|\n|-\n|1982\n|''Soup for One''\n|Allan's Mother\n|\n|-\n|1982\n|''[[Love Child (1982 film)|Love Child]]''\n|Mrs. Sturgis\n|\n|-\n|1983\n|''[[Baby It's You]]''\n|Mrs. Rosen\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[The Killing Fields (film)|The Killing Fields]]''\n|Sydney Schanberg's Sister\n|\n|-\n|1985\n|''[[Year of the Dragon (film)|Year of the Dragon]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1986\n|''[[Big Trouble in Little China]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[Prince of Darkness (film)|Prince of Darkness]]''\n|Bag lady\n|\n|-\n|1987\n|''[[The Last Emperor]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1988\n|''[[Mystic Pizza]]''\n|Mrs. Arujo\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Mr. and Mrs. Bridge]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1991\n|''[[Class Action (film)|Class Action]]''\n|Estelle Ward\n|\n|-\n|1992\n|''[[The Lover (1992 film)|The Lover]]''\n|Casting director\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[Little Buddha]]''\n|Tibetian casting: New York\n|\n|-\n|1993\n|''[[M. Butterfly (film)|M.